League of Honour <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ustormtower.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stormtower</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Travelling Circus</span><br>  Posts: 310<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/9/02 11:14:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1031.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Some considerations</span><hr size=1> I firmly believe that the ruleset for Firiona Vie help in making the game run the way it is supposed to go.  There are a few weird things that may be bugs, but the ruleset has made the game &quot;more realistic&quot;.<br>
<br>
1.  All classes can bind only in towns.  It never made sense (for me) to have different bind rules for melee vs. caster.  It never made sense for a caster to reincarnate in a non-friendly zone.<br>
<br>
2.  No common language.  Although the merchants seem to be masters at all languages, even the language of the races they abhor.  The language barrier is a very realistic aspect of roleplaying.<br>
<br>
3.  Trivial Loot Code.  You'll find my arguments in this forum.  I just wish they took it away from quest-component and tradeskill-component items (and the only thing preventing them from fixing those is the amount of time it would require).<br>
<br>
4.  Alignments.  I like this A LOT!  It certainly reinforces the view that the dieties of Norrath have a far more active hand in the characters' lives.  It doesn't matter if a paladin fell in love with a shadowknight, they can't hunt together because the gods prevent them from doing so!<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/10/02 3:35:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1031.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> I restarted ..</span><hr size=1> .. on FV after playing 3 chars to post 50 and one to 60 on a normal blue server.  Quit about a year ago, tried AO, got fed up with the bugs and decided to try EQ again.  First thing I did was peruse the server boards for the smaller servers.  FV seemed to have the most fun people and that's why I'm here.<br>
<br>
Second thing, of course, is the new ruleset.  In some ways it's an impediment to both normal play and role-play.  In other ways, it likely contributes to keeping this server small.  Small is very good.  It means no one can be anonymous for long and thus griefers won't like it here.  'Course it also makes it hard to form pickup-groups.  I'd say that if you don't plan on joining a guild sometime before your class hits it's personal &quot;solo-wall&quot;, FV probably isn't for you.<br>
<br>
In general, FV brings back memories of how EQ was just weeks after release.  Everyone at least makes a stab at role-playing and people here mostly want to have fun grouping together rather than rushing like mad lemmings from one hot-loot spot to the next.  Read the rule-set on Verant's web site and if the deviations from normal servers sounds tolerable to you, come try FV.  It's a lot of fun. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#A62A2A>- </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie>Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1>Firiona Vie General Chat</a> <font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href="http://www.firiona-vie.com/">Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font> <center><a href="http://www.firiona-vie.com/fvchat.html" target="_blank"><h3>Chat Room</a></h3></center> <br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.5<br>Copyright ©1999-2001 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  